  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What does beta-alanine do for exercise?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Beta-alanine is a non-essential amino acid that increases intramuscular carnosine concentrations. Carnosine acts as an intracellular pH buffer — it neutralizes hydrogen ions (H+) that accumulate during high-intensity exercise. These hydrogen ions cause the burning sensation in your muscles and contribute to fatigue. By buffering acid buildup, carnosine extends the time before muscular fatigue sets in, allowing you to perform more reps, sustain higher intensity, and delay exhaustion. A 2012 meta-analysis in Amino Acids analyzing 15 studies found that beta-alanine supplementation improved exercise capacity by 2.85% — with the greatest benefits in activities lasting 1-4 minutes.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much beta-alanine should I take daily?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The clinically effective dose is 3.2-6.4g per day, typically split into 2-4 smaller doses to minimize the tingling sensation (paresthesia). The International Society of Sports Nutrition (ISSN) position stand recommends at least 3.2g daily for a minimum of 4 weeks to achieve a meaningful increase in muscle carnosine levels (typically 20-30% increase at 4 weeks, 40-60% at 10+ weeks). Beta-alanine is a loading supplement — its benefits are cumulative and depend on consistent daily intake over weeks, not acute pre-workout dosing.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the tingling sensation from beta-alanine?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The tingling, itching, or prickling sensation after taking beta-alanine is called paresthesia. It occurs because beta-alanine activates sensory neurons (Mas-related G protein-coupled receptors) in the skin. Paresthesia is harmless and typically affects the face, neck, and backs of the hands. It usually begins 15-20 minutes after ingestion and lasts 60-90 minutes. Severity is dose-dependent — higher single doses cause more intense tingling. Splitting the daily dose into smaller portions (800mg-1.6g per dose) significantly reduces or eliminates paresthesia. Sustained-release formulations (like CarnoSyn SR) also minimize tingling.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is CarnoSyn and why does it matter?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'CarnoSyn is the only patented, clinically studied form of beta-alanine, manufactured by Natural Alternatives International (NAI). It has been used in over 55 clinical studies demonstrating its efficacy and safety. CarnoSyn is also the only beta-alanine with New Dietary Ingredient (NDI) notification status with the FDA, and it undergoes rigorous testing for purity, potency, and absence of contaminants. Generic beta-alanine may be sourced from less regulated suppliers and may not have the same quality assurance. For athletes who want the highest confidence in ingredient quality, CarnoSyn is the gold standard.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How long does beta-alanine take to work?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Beta-alanine is not an acute performance enhancer — it works through cumulative muscle carnosine loading. At the standard dose of 3.2-6.4g daily, muscle carnosine levels increase approximately 20-30% after 4 weeks, 40-60% after 10-12 weeks, and can reach 80%+ elevation with sustained supplementation over several months. This means you will not notice performance benefits from a single dose. Consistent daily supplementation for at least 2-4 weeks is required before meaningful improvements in muscular endurance become apparent. However, once carnosine levels are elevated, they remain elevated for 6-15 weeks after discontinuation.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I take beta-alanine on rest days?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, and you should. Beta-alanine works through carnosine loading, which requires consistent daily intake regardless of training schedule. Taking beta-alanine only on training days will slow the carnosine loading process and reduce its effectiveness. Think of beta-alanine like creatine — the benefits come from maintaining elevated muscle stores through daily supplementation, not from acute pre-workout dosing. On rest days, take your beta-alanine at any time — with or without food.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Is beta-alanine safe long-term?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Long-term beta-alanine supplementation appears safe based on available evidence. Studies lasting up to 24 weeks at doses of 3.2-6.4g daily have reported no serious adverse effects beyond paresthesia. The ISSN position stand concludes that beta-alanine supplementation at recommended doses is safe for healthy individuals. However, beta-alanine may lower taurine levels (they compete for the same transporter), so individuals supplementing long-term may consider adding taurine (1-3g daily) to maintain balance. People with epilepsy should consult their physician, as animal studies suggest high-dose beta-alanine may affect taurine-dependent neurological pathways.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I stack beta-alanine with creatine and citrulline?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes — this is considered the gold standard performance supplement stack. Beta-alanine buffers acid (extending endurance), creatine regenerates ATP (increasing power and strength), and citrulline enhances blood flow (improving pump and nutrient delivery). These three supplements work through completely independent mechanisms with no negative interactions. The ISSN identifies all three as evidence-based ergogenic aids with the highest level of evidence. Together, they provide the most comprehensive, science-backed performance support available.' } },
  ],
};
