    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Beta-Alanine Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>What does beta-alanine do for exercise?</summary><p>Beta-alanine increases muscle carnosine, which buffers acid buildup during high-intensity exercise. This delays fatigue and extends endurance, with greatest benefits in activities lasting 1-4 minutes.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much beta-alanine should I take daily?</summary><p>3.2-6.4g daily, split into 2-4 doses to manage tingling. At least 4 weeks of daily use is needed for meaningful carnosine loading.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the tingling sensation from beta-alanine?</summary><p>Paresthesia — a harmless tingling/itching caused by beta-alanine activating sensory neurons. It is dose-dependent and can be minimized by splitting doses or using sustained-release forms.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is CarnoSyn and why does it matter?</summary><p>CarnoSyn is the only patented, clinically studied beta-alanine used in 55+ studies. It has FDA NDI notification and rigorous purity testing, making it the gold standard ingredient.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does beta-alanine take to work?</summary><p>2-4 weeks minimum. Carnosine increases 20-30% at 4 weeks, 40-60% at 10-12 weeks. It is a loading supplement, not an acute performance enhancer.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take beta-alanine on rest days?</summary><p>Yes, and you should. Daily loading is required for carnosine accumulation. Take at any time on rest days.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is beta-alanine safe long-term?</summary><p>Studies up to 24 weeks show no serious adverse effects. Consider adding 1-3g taurine daily to offset beta-alanine's taurine-depleting effect. Consult a physician if you have epilepsy.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I stack beta-alanine with creatine and citrulline?</summary><p>Yes — this is the gold standard performance stack. All three work through independent mechanisms with no negative interactions. The ISSN rates all three as top-tier ergogenic aids.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> Beta-alanine paresthesia is harmless but can be alarming if unexpected. Start with a lower dose (1.6g) and increase gradually. Individuals with epilepsy should consult their physician before taking beta-alanine. If you experience persistent or severe tingling, reduce your single-dose amount.</p>
    </div>

